{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bab6ea84e3bba62f", "type": "tool_result", "content": "lyrics of songs performed over decades at Sanremo, it is possible to track shifts in\nlanguage use, thematic focus, and emotional expression within the context of Italian\nculture, offering a deeper understanding of the Italian musical landscape.\n\n3 Related work\nRecent research has highlighted a marked simplification in the musical structure of\npopular songs over time. For instance, Di Marco et al. [16] analyzed over 20,000 com-\npositions using tools from network science, revealing a significant reduction in musical\ncomplexity across diverse genres. Similarly, Hamilton and Pearce [17] examined U.S.\nchart-topping melodies from 1950 to 2023 and identified a decreasing trend in melodic\nvariety and unpredictability. While these studies focus on the structural and harmonic\ndimensions of music, our work diverges by addressing the evolution of lyrics.\n    Previous approaches to analyzing musical texts have applied various methods,\nincluding word2vec and bag-of-words. For instance, [18] focused on rap lyrics, using\nword embeddings to capture semantic meaning. On the other hand, [19] introduced\ngraph-based representation to analyze and interpret popular music lyrics.\n    In this paper, a key factor driving the adoption of transformer embeddings and\nsemantic similarity measures is their alignment with human perception. In particu-\nlar, [20] recently found a significant correlation between semantic similarity scores\nand perceptual similarity judgments, suggesting that embedding-based approaches can\neffectively approximate human cognitive evaluations of textual similarity; while they\nutilized the all-MiniLM-L6-v21 model, in our analysis we use more recent embed-\nding models (see Section 5) because of their superior performance in benchmark\nevaluations2 (see [21]).\n    In [22] the authors employed embeddings also to trace trends in textual evolution,\nhighlighting the increasing significance of semantic embeddings in the humanities.\nTheir work supports some hypotheses from literary studies while offering fresh\nperspectives on the development of early modernism in German poetry.\n    Furthermore, in [23] it was discovered that lyrics have become simpler over time\nacross several dimensions. While the authors analyzed lyrical trends using handcrafted\ndescriptors—such as lexical diversity, structural patterns, and rhyme characteris-\ntics—our approach differs by utilizing semantic embeddings. At the conclusion of their\nstudy, the authors emphasize the broader implications of lyrical analysis, noting that\nsong lyrics remain an underexplored but valuable resource for understanding cultural\nartifacts and societal shifts. Our research aligns with this perspective, demonstrating\nhow semantic similarity analysis can reveal evolving lyrical patterns, thus contributing\n\n 1\n     https://huggingface.co/sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2\n 2\n     https://huggingface.co/spaces/mteb/leaderboard\n\n\n\n                                                   4\n\fto the broader discourse on cultural and artistic transformations in music. Addition-\nally, our findings, derived from a prominent Italian music festival, reaffirm the trends\nobserved in their more general dataset.\n\n4 Overview\nThis work is structured as follows. Section 5 introduces the dataset we collected and\nthe embedding models used throughout the experiments, along with the correspond-\ning notation. Section 6 presents the techniques employed to analyze the evolution of\nsemantic similarity over the years in the lyrics of songs performed at the Sanremo\nFestival finals. Each subsection focuses on a specific type of analysis. See Figure 1 for\nan example that shows in general how the analysis is performed. Finally, in Section 7,\nwe discuss the results of the experiments described in Section 6. Section 8 concludes\nwith a brief discussion of potential future work in this area.\n\n5 Dataset and Embeddings Used\nFor each year Y ∈ Y = {1951, . . . , 2025} in which the Sanremo festival took place, we\ncollected the lyrics of the nY finalist songs, denoted as l1Y , . . . , lnYY .\n    To analyze the similarities between songs, we considered a set E of different textual\nembedding models. Specifically, we considered E = {i, o, c}, where:\n• i represents the sentence transformer model intfloat/multilingual-e5-large3 ,\n  see [24] for details;\n• o corresponds to OpenAI’s embedding model text-embedding-3-large4 ,\n• c denotes colbert-xm5 , see [25, 26] for details.\n   Note that hereinafter we will generally talk about similarity between embeddings.\nWhen the embeddings considered are i and o we call similarity the standard cosine\nsimilarity. When the embedding considered is c, since the “MaxSim” similarity S ,\ncommonly used for c, is not symmetric (see [25, 26]), we call similarity between two\nc-embeddings A and B , the quantity 21 [S (A, B ) + S (B, A)].\n\n6 Cross-Year Analysis of Semantic Similarity\nIn this section, we present different approaches for analyzing the similarities between\nsongs across the years. The goal is to compute, for each pair of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y ×Y , a\n                                                                                                 n\nmeasure that quantifies the average semantic similarity between the lyrics lY1 a , . . . , lYaYa\n                     nY\nand lY1 b , . . . , lYb b . This allows us to examine the evolution of lyrical similarity over time.\n\n6.1 Full-Text Similarity\nWe first analyze song similarities using embeddings computed from the full lyrics.\nGiven an embedding model α ∈ E , we construct, for each pair of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y ,\n\n  3\n      https://huggingface.co/intfloat/multilingual-e5-large\n  4\n      https://openai.com/index/new-embedding-models-and-api-updates/\n  5\n      https://huggingface.co/antoinelouis/colbert-xm\n\n\n\n                                                  5\n\fan nYa ×nYb similarity matrix FYαa ,Yb , where each entry represents the cosine similarity\nbetween the embeddings (obtained with α) of the songs from Ya and Yb . An example\nis shown in Figure 2.\n\n\n\n\n                                             i\nFig. 2 Example of the similarity matrix F1951,1960    , where values are normalized such that the\nminimum is 0 and the maximum is 1. Rows and columns correspond to the titles of the finalist\nsongs from 1951 and 1960, respectively. This grid shows the similarity in the full text of each song\npairing, with warmer colors indicating more alike lyrics and cooler colors indicating less similarity.\nThe normalization allows for easy comparison of relative similarities.\n\n\n   Next, we compute similarity measures for all possible year pairs (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y ,\navoiding the diagonal when Ya = Yb . Specifically, for each embedding model α ∈ E ,\nwe derive the following matrices:\n    α\n• F mean which is built evaluating for each (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y , the mean of all values in\n                                                                                      α\n  FYαa ,Yb (excluding the diagonal if Ya = Yb ) obtaining a first |Y| × |Y| matrix. F mean\n  is obtained normalizing the latter matrix in such a way that that the minimum\n  value is 0 and the highest is 1.\n    α                             α\n• F med which is analogous to F mean but considering the median (instead of the mean)\n                                           α\n  similarity score, then normalized as F mean .\n    α\n• F q whose element corresponding to (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y is the proportion of elements\n  of FYαa ,Yb that exceeds the q -quantile threshold, computed across all song pairs in\n  the dataset. Selecting a high value of q , it represents the percentage of song pairs for\n  each couple of years which are more similar than the majority of the other possible\n  pairs.\n\n\n                                                  6\n\fSee Figure 3 for an example.\n\n\n\n\n                    i\nFig. 3 Matrix F 0.75 , as defined in Section 6.1, shows the percentage of song pairs between any two\nyears where the full lyrics exceed the similarity of 75% of all other song pairs. Warmer colors indicate\na larger proportion of unusually high lyrical similarity between those years.\n\n\n\n\n6.2 Portion-Based Similarity\nA potential limitation of full-text analysis is that two songs might be highly similar\neven if their overall similarity score is not particularly high. Instead of comparing\nentire lyrics, we introduce a measure that assigns greater importance to similar textual\nsegments.\n      For each song lYi , where Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }, we segment it into portions\np(lY ) = p1 , . . . , pmiY , where miY ≥ 1, ensuring that lYi is reconstructed from the\n    i\n\nordered union of this portions. The portions are extracted using an LLM (namely\ngemini-1.5-flash6 ) prompted to segment lyrics into portions made up of more than\none sentence. Hence, to evaluate the similarity between two songs lYi a and lYj b , for some\nYa , Yb ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }; j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }, we consider their portions p(lYi a ) and\np(lYj b ) and compute the similarity between the α-embedding of all the couples (pi , pj ),\n\n  6\n      https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/models\n\n\n\n                                                     7\n\ffor α ∈ E , pi ∈ p(lYi a ) and pj ∈ p(lYj b ), obtaining a miYa × mjYb matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ). The\nelement (u, v ) of the matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ) is the similarity between the α-embedding of\nthe u-th portion of lYi a and the one of the v -th portion of lYj b . A concrete example of\nsimilar portions of text could be found in Table 2.\n    Then, to visualize similarities between songs for a couple of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y\nbased on their parts, we define the nYa × nYb matrix PYα,k          a ,Yb\n                                                                          , for some arbitrary small\n(see Remark 1) positive integer k , whose element (i, j ) is the sum of the k highest\nvalues of the matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ). In the matrices PYα,k a ,Yb\n                                                                       with Ya = Yb we avoid the\ndiagonal values. The matrix PYα,k  a ,Yb\n                                         is the analogous, but reasoning on songs’portions,\nof the matrix FYαa ,Yb (full-text similarity).\n    As we did in Section 6.1, in order to have matrices that allow us to visualize some\nsimilarity measures across years, we define the following (normalized) |Y|×|Y| matrices\n  α,k      α,k     α,k                                                                       α\nP mean , P med , P q , which are defined for any α ∈ E , exactly as, respectively, F mean ,\n  α       α\nF med , F q but using the matrices PYα,k   a ,Yb\n                                                 instead of FYαa ,Yb , for (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y . See\nFigure 4 for an example.\n\nRemark 1 k must be smaller than the minimum of {miYa mjYb : i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈\n{1, . . . , nYb }}.\n\n\n\n6.3 Topic-Based Similarity\nAnother approach to evaluating semantic similarity is through the analysis of lyrics\ntopics. To achieve this, in a first step we identify the primary topics tYi for each song\nliY , where Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }. The identification process is done using a LLM\n(namely gemini-1.5-flash) prompted to, given the lyrics of a song, return a list\nof the main topics treated in the text. Once topics are extracted for each song, we\ncompute the similarity between the topics tYi a and tYj b of two generic songs liYa and\nljYb , for Ya , Yb ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }. This is done by converting\nthe lists of topics into strings, which are then embedded using α ∈ E . The similarity\nbetween two songs based on the topics is thus the similarity between the α-embedding\nof these strings. Therefore it is straightforward to build, for each (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y , the\nnYa ×nYb matrix TYαa ,Yb containing the topic similarities between all the song presented\nat the Sanremo festival in Ya and Yb (avoiding the diagonal if Ya = Yb ). TYαa ,Yb is\nanalogous to FYαa ,Yb and PYα,ka ,Yb\n                                      (defined in Sections 6.1 and 6.2), but topics based.\nOnce we compute all the matrices TYαa ,Yb , in order to analyze the evolutions of topics\n                                                                                       α       α\nsimilarity across years, we compute the (normalized) |Y| × |Y| matrices T mean , T med ,\n   α                                                                α        α      α\nT q exactly as done in Section 6.1 for, respectively, F mean , F med , F q but using the\nmatrices TYαa ,Yb instead of FYαa ,Yb , for (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y . See Figure 5 for an example.\n\n6.4 Word-Based Similarity\nIn this section, we adopt a different analytical approach, shifting from embedding-\nbased models to a purely statistical evaluation of word occurrences. By focusing on\n\n\n                                                  8\n\f                     o,3\nFig. 4 Matrix P mean , as defined in Section 6.2, presents the average similarity based on the top 3\nmost similar sections of lyrics between songs from any two years. Warmer colors suggest a greater\nhomogeneity in the lyrical content, specifically within the most comparable segments, between the\nsongs of those two years.\n\n\nwords co-occurrence patterns across lyrics and years, it is possible to assess whether\nthe results gained through embedding-based techniques align with the statistical ones.\n    For each lYi , for Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }, we considered both the lyric as-is and\na normalized one ˜lYi obtained converting all verbs to their infinitive form, transforming\nall text to lowercase, and reducing all nouns and adjectives to their singular form.\nThe normalized text ˜lYi is obtained prompting a LLM (namely gemini-1.5-flash)\nto transform the text lYi as explained above.\n\n                                                                                     i\nRemark 2 Although in principle the normalization of the text to pass from a lyric lY   to its\n                     i                                                              7\nnormalized version ˜lY could be done even relying on simpler methods (like the spaCy python", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "7adfc9b8-6936-46dd-9c20-5108afde690a", "uuid": "07a543e3-a542-4664-ae14-641284aeb953", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T13:14:12.963Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "lyrics of songs performed over decades at Sanremo, it is possible to track shifts in\nlanguage use, thematic focus, and emotional expression within the context of Italian\nculture, offering a deeper understanding of the Italian musical landscape.\n\n3 Related work\nRecent research has highlighted a marked simplification in the musical structure of\npopular songs over time. For instance, Di Marco et al. [16] analyzed over 20,000 com-\npositions using tools from network science, revealing a significant reduction in musical\ncomplexity across diverse genres. Similarly, Hamilton and Pearce [17] examined U.S.\nchart-topping melodies from 1950 to 2023 and identified a decreasing trend in melodic\nvariety and unpredictability. While these studies focus on the structural and harmonic\ndimensions of music, our work diverges by addressing the evolution of lyrics.\n    Previous approaches to analyzing musical texts have applied various methods,\nincluding word2vec and bag-of-words. For instance, [18] focused on rap lyrics, using\nword embeddings to capture semantic meaning. On the other hand, [19] introduced\ngraph-based representation to analyze and interpret popular music lyrics.\n    In this paper, a key factor driving the adoption of transformer embeddings and\nsemantic similarity measures is their alignment with human perception. In particu-\nlar, [20] recently found a significant correlation between semantic similarity scores\nand perceptual similarity judgments, suggesting that embedding-based approaches can\neffectively approximate human cognitive evaluations of textual similarity; while they\nutilized the all-MiniLM-L6-v21 model, in our analysis we use more recent embed-\nding models (see Section 5) because of their superior performance in benchmark\nevaluations2 (see [21]).\n    In [22] the authors employed embeddings also to trace trends in textual evolution,\nhighlighting the increasing significance of semantic embeddings in the humanities.\nTheir work supports some hypotheses from literary studies while offering fresh\nperspectives on the development of early modernism in German poetry.\n    Furthermore, in [23] it was discovered that lyrics have become simpler over time\nacross several dimensions. While the authors analyzed lyrical trends using handcrafted\ndescriptors—such as lexical diversity, structural patterns, and rhyme characteris-\ntics—our approach differs by utilizing semantic embeddings. At the conclusion of their\nstudy, the authors emphasize the broader implications of lyrical analysis, noting that\nsong lyrics remain an underexplored but valuable resource for understanding cultural\nartifacts and societal shifts. Our research aligns with this perspective, demonstrating\nhow semantic similarity analysis can reveal evolving lyrical patterns, thus contributing\n\n 1\n     https://huggingface.co/sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2\n 2\n     https://huggingface.co/spaces/mteb/leaderboard\n\n\n\n                                                   4\n\fto the broader discourse on cultural and artistic transformations in music. Addition-\nally, our findings, derived from a prominent Italian music festival, reaffirm the trends\nobserved in their more general dataset.\n\n4 Overview\nThis work is structured as follows. Section 5 introduces the dataset we collected and\nthe embedding models used throughout the experiments, along with the correspond-\ning notation. Section 6 presents the techniques employed to analyze the evolution of\nsemantic similarity over the years in the lyrics of songs performed at the Sanremo\nFestival finals. Each subsection focuses on a specific type of analysis. See Figure 1 for\nan example that shows in general how the analysis is performed. Finally, in Section 7,\nwe discuss the results of the experiments described in Section 6. Section 8 concludes\nwith a brief discussion of potential future work in this area.\n\n5 Dataset and Embeddings Used\nFor each year Y ∈ Y = {1951, . . . , 2025} in which the Sanremo festival took place, we\ncollected the lyrics of the nY finalist songs, denoted as l1Y , . . . , lnYY .\n    To analyze the similarities between songs, we considered a set E of different textual\nembedding models. Specifically, we considered E = {i, o, c}, where:\n• i represents the sentence transformer model intfloat/multilingual-e5-large3 ,\n  see [24] for details;\n• o corresponds to OpenAI’s embedding model text-embedding-3-large4 ,\n• c denotes colbert-xm5 , see [25, 26] for details.\n   Note that hereinafter we will generally talk about similarity between embeddings.\nWhen the embeddings considered are i and o we call similarity the standard cosine\nsimilarity. When the embedding considered is c, since the “MaxSim” similarity S ,\ncommonly used for c, is not symmetric (see [25, 26]), we call similarity between two\nc-embeddings A and B , the quantity 21 [S (A, B ) + S (B, A)].\n\n6 Cross-Year Analysis of Semantic Similarity\nIn this section, we present different approaches for analyzing the similarities between\nsongs across the years. The goal is to compute, for each pair of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y ×Y , a\n                                                                                                 n\nmeasure that quantifies the average semantic similarity between the lyrics lY1 a , . . . , lYaYa\n                     nY\nand lY1 b , . . . , lYb b . This allows us to examine the evolution of lyrical similarity over time.\n\n6.1 Full-Text Similarity\nWe first analyze song similarities using embeddings computed from the full lyrics.\nGiven an embedding model α ∈ E , we construct, for each pair of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y ,\n\n  3\n      https://huggingface.co/intfloat/multilingual-e5-large\n  4\n      https://openai.com/index/new-embedding-models-and-api-updates/\n  5\n      https://huggingface.co/antoinelouis/colbert-xm\n\n\n\n                                                  5\n\fan nYa ×nYb similarity matrix FYαa ,Yb , where each entry represents the cosine similarity\nbetween the embeddings (obtained with α) of the songs from Ya and Yb . An example\nis shown in Figure 2.\n\n\n\n\n                                             i\nFig. 2 Example of the similarity matrix F1951,1960    , where values are normalized such that the\nminimum is 0 and the maximum is 1. Rows and columns correspond to the titles of the finalist\nsongs from 1951 and 1960, respectively. This grid shows the similarity in the full text of each song\npairing, with warmer colors indicating more alike lyrics and cooler colors indicating less similarity.\nThe normalization allows for easy comparison of relative similarities.\n\n\n   Next, we compute similarity measures for all possible year pairs (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y ,\navoiding the diagonal when Ya = Yb . Specifically, for each embedding model α ∈ E ,\nwe derive the following matrices:\n    α\n• F mean which is built evaluating for each (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y , the mean of all values in\n                                                                                      α\n  FYαa ,Yb (excluding the diagonal if Ya = Yb ) obtaining a first |Y| × |Y| matrix. F mean\n  is obtained normalizing the latter matrix in such a way that that the minimum\n  value is 0 and the highest is 1.\n    α                             α\n• F med which is analogous to F mean but considering the median (instead of the mean)\n                                           α\n  similarity score, then normalized as F mean .\n    α\n• F q whose element corresponding to (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y is the proportion of elements\n  of FYαa ,Yb that exceeds the q -quantile threshold, computed across all song pairs in\n  the dataset. Selecting a high value of q , it represents the percentage of song pairs for\n  each couple of years which are more similar than the majority of the other possible\n  pairs.\n\n\n                                                  6\n\fSee Figure 3 for an example.\n\n\n\n\n                    i\nFig. 3 Matrix F 0.75 , as defined in Section 6.1, shows the percentage of song pairs between any two\nyears where the full lyrics exceed the similarity of 75% of all other song pairs. Warmer colors indicate\na larger proportion of unusually high lyrical similarity between those years.\n\n\n\n\n6.2 Portion-Based Similarity\nA potential limitation of full-text analysis is that two songs might be highly similar\neven if their overall similarity score is not particularly high. Instead of comparing\nentire lyrics, we introduce a measure that assigns greater importance to similar textual\nsegments.\n      For each song lYi , where Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }, we segment it into portions\np(lY ) = p1 , . . . , pmiY , where miY ≥ 1, ensuring that lYi is reconstructed from the\n    i\n\nordered union of this portions. The portions are extracted using an LLM (namely\ngemini-1.5-flash6 ) prompted to segment lyrics into portions made up of more than\none sentence. Hence, to evaluate the similarity between two songs lYi a and lYj b , for some\nYa , Yb ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }; j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }, we consider their portions p(lYi a ) and\np(lYj b ) and compute the similarity between the α-embedding of all the couples (pi , pj ),\n\n  6\n      https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/models\n\n\n\n                                                     7\n\ffor α ∈ E , pi ∈ p(lYi a ) and pj ∈ p(lYj b ), obtaining a miYa × mjYb matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ). The\nelement (u, v ) of the matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ) is the similarity between the α-embedding of\nthe u-th portion of lYi a and the one of the v -th portion of lYj b . A concrete example of\nsimilar portions of text could be found in Table 2.\n    Then, to visualize similarities between songs for a couple of years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y\nbased on their parts, we define the nYa × nYb matrix PYα,k          a ,Yb\n                                                                          , for some arbitrary small\n(see Remark 1) positive integer k , whose element (i, j ) is the sum of the k highest\nvalues of the matrix Πα (lYi a , lYj b ). In the matrices PYα,k a ,Yb\n                                                                       with Ya = Yb we avoid the\ndiagonal values. The matrix PYα,k  a ,Yb\n                                         is the analogous, but reasoning on songs’portions,\nof the matrix FYαa ,Yb (full-text similarity).\n    As we did in Section 6.1, in order to have matrices that allow us to visualize some\nsimilarity measures across years, we define the following (normalized) |Y|×|Y| matrices\n  α,k      α,k     α,k                                                                       α\nP mean , P med , P q , which are defined for any α ∈ E , exactly as, respectively, F mean ,\n  α       α\nF med , F q but using the matrices PYα,k   a ,Yb\n                                                 instead of FYαa ,Yb , for (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y . See\nFigure 4 for an example.\n\nRemark 1 k must be smaller than the minimum of {miYa mjYb : i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈\n{1, . . . , nYb }}.\n\n\n\n6.3 Topic-Based Similarity\nAnother approach to evaluating semantic similarity is through the analysis of lyrics\ntopics. To achieve this, in a first step we identify the primary topics tYi for each song\nliY , where Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }. The identification process is done using a LLM\n(namely gemini-1.5-flash) prompted to, given the lyrics of a song, return a list\nof the main topics treated in the text. Once topics are extracted for each song, we\ncompute the similarity between the topics tYi a and tYj b of two generic songs liYa and\nljYb , for Ya , Yb ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }. This is done by converting\nthe lists of topics into strings, which are then embedded using α ∈ E . The similarity\nbetween two songs based on the topics is thus the similarity between the α-embedding\nof these strings. Therefore it is straightforward to build, for each (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y , the\nnYa ×nYb matrix TYαa ,Yb containing the topic similarities between all the song presented\nat the Sanremo festival in Ya and Yb (avoiding the diagonal if Ya = Yb ). TYαa ,Yb is\nanalogous to FYαa ,Yb and PYα,ka ,Yb\n                                      (defined in Sections 6.1 and 6.2), but topics based.\nOnce we compute all the matrices TYαa ,Yb , in order to analyze the evolutions of topics\n                                                                                       α       α\nsimilarity across years, we compute the (normalized) |Y| × |Y| matrices T mean , T med ,\n   α                                                                α        α      α\nT q exactly as done in Section 6.1 for, respectively, F mean , F med , F q but using the\nmatrices TYαa ,Yb instead of FYαa ,Yb , for (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y . See Figure 5 for an example.\n\n6.4 Word-Based Similarity\nIn this section, we adopt a different analytical approach, shifting from embedding-\nbased models to a purely statistical evaluation of word occurrences. By focusing on\n\n\n                                                  8\n\f                     o,3\nFig. 4 Matrix P mean , as defined in Section 6.2, presents the average similarity based on the top 3\nmost similar sections of lyrics between songs from any two years. Warmer colors suggest a greater\nhomogeneity in the lyrical content, specifically within the most comparable segments, between the\nsongs of those two years.\n\n\nwords co-occurrence patterns across lyrics and years, it is possible to assess whether\nthe results gained through embedding-based techniques align with the statistical ones.\n    For each lYi , for Y ∈ Y and i ∈ {1, . . . , nY }, we considered both the lyric as-is and\na normalized one ˜lYi obtained converting all verbs to their infinitive form, transforming\nall text to lowercase, and reducing all nouns and adjectives to their singular form.\nThe normalized text ˜lYi is obtained prompting a LLM (namely gemini-1.5-flash)\nto transform the text lYi as explained above.\n\n                                                                                     i\nRemark 2 Although in principle the normalization of the text to pass from a lyric lY   to its\n                     i                                                              7\nnormalized version ˜lY could be done even relying on simpler methods (like the spaCy python", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
