{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a0a0475f9d8ac916", "type": "tool_result", "content": "normalized version ˜lY could be done even relying on simpler methods (like the spaCy python\nlibrary [27]) rather than LLM, we observed that even when using Italian-specific models,\nthe resulting forms were often suboptimal—especially for verbs, which were lemmatized into\nunexpected or non-infinitive forms. For this reason, we opted for an LLM-based approach,\nwhich, in our experiments, produced more consistent and intuitive results for the data at\nhand. However, this was not a formal evaluation, but rather a practical choice based on\nmanual inspection.\n\n  7\n      https://spacy.io/\n\n\n\n                                                 9\n\f    To focus only on significant words, we filter each lyric (both original and normal-\nized) to retain only verbs, nouns, and adjectives. This filtering is based on automatic\npart-of-speech (PoS) tagging performed using the spaCy Python library with the\nit core news lg model, which is specifically trained for Italian. The extraction is car-\nried out in two ways: preserving repeated words or not, using the transformations ρ\nand ρ̃ on a generic text T :\n• ρ(T ) = list of all significant words in T with repetition;\n• ρ̃(T ) = list of all significant words in T without repetition.\n      So, for example, if the initial text is T = “my Home is a very sweet home”, its\ncleaned version T̃ would be “my home be a very sweet home”. Then ρ(T ) = [Home,\nis, sweet, home] = ρ̃(T ), ρ(T̃ ) = [home, be, sweet, home], ρ̃(T̃ ) = [home, be, sweet].\n      In this case, the “similarity” between two lyrics lYi a and lYj b , for Ya , Yb ∈ Y and\ni ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }, is given by ρ(lYi a ) ∩ ρ(lYj b ) (resp. ρ(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ(˜lYj b ) on\nthe normalized text), if we want to give more weight to the repeated words, and by\nρ̃(lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(lYj b ) (resp. ρ̃(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(˜lYj b )) otherwise.\n      Now, that we defined the similarity for this type of analysis, we build for each pair\nof years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y four different matrices WYι a ,Yb , ι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4}, containing\nthe similarities between the songs in Ya and Yb defined as above, considering the four\n\n\n\n\n                   c\nFig. 5 Matrix T med , as defined in Section 6.3, illustrates the median similarity of the main themes\ndiscussed in songs between any two years. Warmer colors indicate a higher thematic similarity.\n\n\n\n                                                      10\n\fcombination of as-is or normalized text and intersection with or without repetition.\nMore precisely, the similarity between lYi a and lYj b will be represented in WY1a ,Yb , WY2a ,Yb ,\nWY3a ,Yb , WY4a ,Yb as, respectively, ρ(lYi a ) ∩ ρ(lYj b ), ρ̃(lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(lYj b ), ρ(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ(˜lYj b ), ρ̃(˜lYi a ) ∩\nρ̃(˜lYj b ). This is summarized in Table 1.\n\n                                       Table 1 Notation for the WYι a ,Yb ,\n                                       ι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4} and (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y,\n                                       obtained through the intersections\n                                       of ρ and ρ̃ transformations, applied\n                                       to lyrics in their original (“as-is”)\n                                       and normalized forms.\n\n                                                                 ρ           ρ̃\n                                              as-is         WY1a ,Yb     WY2a ,Yb\n                                          normalized        WY3a ,Yb     WY4a ,Yb\n\n\n\n\n    Then, to analyze the word-based similarities, defined above, across the years, we\nproceed as in the previous sections, see Section 6.1 for details, to calculate, for each\n                                                     ι        ι       ι\nι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4} the (normalized) |Y|×|Y| matrices W mean , W med , W q from the matrices\nWYι a ,Yb for all (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y .\n\n7 Results and Discussion\nTo analyze the evolution of similarity (according to the different definitions) over\n                                                     α     α,3   α     ι\nyears, we computed the following matrices F τ , P τ , T τ , W τ , for α ∈ {i, o, c}, ι ∈\n                                                                               α\n{1, 2, 3, 4} and τ ∈ {mean, med, 0.75}. Then, because the matrices F τ (and analo-\n           α,3  α    ι\ngously P τ , T τ , W τ for ι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4}),for α ∈ E , show the same pattern of similarities\nat the varying of τ ∈ {mean, med, 0.75}, we decided to focus on the case τ = mean.\nMoreover, to proceed with just one matrix for P        each type of similarityP analysis con-\n                                                          4      ι                      α\nsidered, we defined the matrices W mean :=                ι=1  W τ , F mean :=   α∈E F mean ,\n  3          P       α3                       P        α\nP mean := α∈E P mean and T mean := α∈E T mean . These latter matrices take into\naccount all the different shades of similarity that the various embeddings or text nor-\nmalization techniques capture in the different similarity analyses. To verify that all\nthese different analyses lead to the same conclusions, we computed the Pearson cor-\nrelation coefficients between the matrices defined above. The results, visible in Figure\n7, showing high values of correlations for all the possible pairs, suggesting that each\nanalysis leads to the same conclusions.\n    Hence, to visualize an overall similarity analysis across years, we defined the |Y| ×\n                                3\n|Y| matrix Z = F mean + P mean + T mean + W mean , which then we normalized in\norder that the minimum values is 0 and the maximum 1, obtaining the final matrix\nZ , visible in Figure 8.\n    The matrix Z suggests that the correlation across the years is increasing with the\nyears, becoming relatively bigger when computed on the last decades. Also the average\n\n\n                                                            11\n\f     Table 2 Examples of high lyrical similarity between segments. Original lyrics were in Italian and translated into English.\n\n      Song 1                  Song 2                   Lyrics 1 (Translated)                            Lyrics 2 (Translated)\n\n                                                       There won’t be another love.\n                                                       There won’t be another time.                     There won’t be\n      Gino Paoli              G. Martinelli\n                                                       The one missing on my path                       Another time, another time.\n      Un altro amore          Il gigante d’acciaio\n                                                       Was you,                                         There won’t be\n      (2013)                  (2020)\n                                                       and no matter what                               Another time, yet again.\n                                                       There won’t be another love.\n\n\n                                                                                                        I... want a quiet life.\n                                                                                                        Because since I was born...\n      Vasco Rossi             Tricarico                I want a reckless life...\n                                                                                                        it’s been\n      Vita spericolata        Vita tranquilla          I want a rude life...\n\n\n\n\n12\n                                                                                                        Desperate... reckless...\n      (1983)                  (2008)                   I want an excessive life...\n                                                                                                        Yet free... truly boundless.\n                                                                                                        I should... no, I shouldn’t...\n\n\n                                                                                                        Looking at fears.\n                                                       A cloud in the sky                               Burning inside the sun.\n                                                       when the sun is out.                             And feeling that with you\n                                                       Swaying in the air,                              I am free.\n      E. De Crescenzo         Anna Tatangelo\n                                                       it drifts on its own.                            Free.\n      Via con me              Libera\n                                                       Your fears drift away.                           Like a cloud in the wind\n      (1983)                  (2015)\n                                                       Adventures are forgotten.                        That sways.\n                                                       But how can you stand                            Unique, unique.\n                                                       being alone at night?                            Like moonlight\n                                                                                                        when it shines.\n\f                  3\nFig. 6 Matrix W mean , as defined in Section 6.4, shows the average overlap in significant normalized\nwords (nouns, verbs, adjectives in base form) used in the lyrics between any two years. Warmer colors\nsuggest greater lexical similarity.\n\n\nsimilarity of the song presented in each year (diagonal of Z ) appears to be growing\nwith the years, as it is clear from the plot in Figure 9, suggesting that the average\nsimilarity across the single editions of the festival is also growing with the years.\n    Moreover, it appears that the songs presented in the festival in the first years are\nless similar to all the others with respect to the recent ones. This is even more clear\nlooking at the plots in Figure 9.\n\n8 Conclusion and future work\nIn conclusion, this paper introduces a novel methodology, leveraging semantic embed-\ndings and large language models, to analyze the evolution of lyrical diversity in musical\ncollections. Applying this framework to the Sanremo Festival, a prominent Italian\nmusic competition, the study reveals a discernible trend towards increasing seman-\ntic homogeneity in lyrics over recent years. This finding is consistent across various\nsimilarity measures, including full-text, portion-based, topic-based, and word-based\nanalyses, as confirmed by high Pearson correlation coefficients between these different\napproaches. This research not only provides a quantitative perspective on the evo-\nlution of Sanremo lyrics but also highlights the efficacy of semantic embeddings in\nuncovering nuanced trends within cultural artifacts.\n\n\n                                                 13\n\f                                                          3\nFig. 7 Pearson correlation coefficients between F mean , P mean , T mean and W mean . The high values\n(warmer colors) suggest a strong positive agreement between the different lyrical similarity analysis\nmethods (full text, portions, topics, and words), indicating consistent patterns in the results.\n\n\n    This study opens avenues for future research:\n• Developing a Python Framework: We plan to release a Python framework\n  based on our methodology that allows researchers to analyze how song similarity\n  evolves based on a given variable (e.g., the release year of the songs). This tool would\n  facilitate large-scale investigations into the temporal dynamics of lyrical similarity\n  across different datasets.\n• Incorporating Musical Difference Metrics: In [20], the authors introduced\n  the Musical Difference metric, which has shown an even stronger correlation with\n  human perceptions of lyrical similarity than standard semantic similarity measures.\n  Future work should explore integrating this metric into our similarity analysis.\n• Validating the Methodology on External Datasets: Since [23] has made their\n  dataset publicly available, it would be valuable to apply our methodology to their\n  dataset and verify whether our approach yields similar findings.\n    By addressing these directions, we aim to refine our methodology, improve its\ninterpretability, and contribute to a broader understanding of how lyrical similarity\nevolves in different musical contexts.\n\nDeclarations\nFunding\nNo funding was received for conducting this study.\n\n\n                                                 14\n\fFig. 8 Matrix Z, as defined in Section 7, sum and normalize the results from all our analysis methods\nto show the general lyrical similarity between any two years, considering full text, key sections,\nthemes, and word choice. Warmer colors indicate a stronger overall similarity.", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "7adfc9b8-6936-46dd-9c20-5108afde690a", "uuid": "5d0928d8-7ae7-4682-8e58-f0477ab88fd5", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T13:14:26.138Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "normalized version ˜lY could be done even relying on simpler methods (like the spaCy python\nlibrary [27]) rather than LLM, we observed that even when using Italian-specific models,\nthe resulting forms were often suboptimal—especially for verbs, which were lemmatized into\nunexpected or non-infinitive forms. For this reason, we opted for an LLM-based approach,\nwhich, in our experiments, produced more consistent and intuitive results for the data at\nhand. However, this was not a formal evaluation, but rather a practical choice based on\nmanual inspection.\n\n  7\n      https://spacy.io/\n\n\n\n                                                 9\n\f    To focus only on significant words, we filter each lyric (both original and normal-\nized) to retain only verbs, nouns, and adjectives. This filtering is based on automatic\npart-of-speech (PoS) tagging performed using the spaCy Python library with the\nit core news lg model, which is specifically trained for Italian. The extraction is car-\nried out in two ways: preserving repeated words or not, using the transformations ρ\nand ρ̃ on a generic text T :\n• ρ(T ) = list of all significant words in T with repetition;\n• ρ̃(T ) = list of all significant words in T without repetition.\n      So, for example, if the initial text is T = “my Home is a very sweet home”, its\ncleaned version T̃ would be “my home be a very sweet home”. Then ρ(T ) = [Home,\nis, sweet, home] = ρ̃(T ), ρ(T̃ ) = [home, be, sweet, home], ρ̃(T̃ ) = [home, be, sweet].\n      In this case, the “similarity” between two lyrics lYi a and lYj b , for Ya , Yb ∈ Y and\ni ∈ {1, . . . , nYa }, j ∈ {1, . . . , nYb }, is given by ρ(lYi a ) ∩ ρ(lYj b ) (resp. ρ(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ(˜lYj b ) on\nthe normalized text), if we want to give more weight to the repeated words, and by\nρ̃(lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(lYj b ) (resp. ρ̃(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(˜lYj b )) otherwise.\n      Now, that we defined the similarity for this type of analysis, we build for each pair\nof years (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y four different matrices WYι a ,Yb , ι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4}, containing\nthe similarities between the songs in Ya and Yb defined as above, considering the four\n\n\n\n\n                   c\nFig. 5 Matrix T med , as defined in Section 6.3, illustrates the median similarity of the main themes\ndiscussed in songs between any two years. Warmer colors indicate a higher thematic similarity.\n\n\n\n                                                      10\n\fcombination of as-is or normalized text and intersection with or without repetition.\nMore precisely, the similarity between lYi a and lYj b will be represented in WY1a ,Yb , WY2a ,Yb ,\nWY3a ,Yb , WY4a ,Yb as, respectively, ρ(lYi a ) ∩ ρ(lYj b ), ρ̃(lYi a ) ∩ ρ̃(lYj b ), ρ(˜lYi a ) ∩ ρ(˜lYj b ), ρ̃(˜lYi a ) ∩\nρ̃(˜lYj b ). This is summarized in Table 1.\n\n                                       Table 1 Notation for the WYι a ,Yb ,\n                                       ι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4} and (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y,\n                                       obtained through the intersections\n                                       of ρ and ρ̃ transformations, applied\n                                       to lyrics in their original (“as-is”)\n                                       and normalized forms.\n\n                                                                 ρ           ρ̃\n                                              as-is         WY1a ,Yb     WY2a ,Yb\n                                          normalized        WY3a ,Yb     WY4a ,Yb\n\n\n\n\n    Then, to analyze the word-based similarities, defined above, across the years, we\nproceed as in the previous sections, see Section 6.1 for details, to calculate, for each\n                                                     ι        ι       ι\nι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4} the (normalized) |Y|×|Y| matrices W mean , W med , W q from the matrices\nWYι a ,Yb for all (Ya , Yb ) ∈ Y × Y .\n\n7 Results and Discussion\nTo analyze the evolution of similarity (according to the different definitions) over\n                                                     α     α,3   α     ι\nyears, we computed the following matrices F τ , P τ , T τ , W τ , for α ∈ {i, o, c}, ι ∈\n                                                                               α\n{1, 2, 3, 4} and τ ∈ {mean, med, 0.75}. Then, because the matrices F τ (and analo-\n           α,3  α    ι\ngously P τ , T τ , W τ for ι ∈ {1, 2, 3, 4}),for α ∈ E , show the same pattern of similarities\nat the varying of τ ∈ {mean, med, 0.75}, we decided to focus on the case τ = mean.\